---
import BaseLayout from "../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
import { creditCardPayoffSchedule } from "../../lib/calc/creditCard";

const title = "Credit Card Payment Payoff Calculator (how to use it)";
const description =
  "How to use a credit card payment payoff calculator to estimate payoff date and interest from your balance, APR, and monthly payment. Educational use only.";

const exampleBalance = 3500;
const exampleApr = 22.5;
const examplePaymentA = 100;
const examplePaymentB = 175;
const payoffA = creditCardPayoffSchedule({ balance: exampleBalance, aprPercent: exampleApr, monthlyPayment: examplePaymentA });
const payoffB = creditCardPayoffSchedule({ balance: exampleBalance, aprPercent: exampleApr, monthlyPayment: examplePaymentB });
const money0 = new Intl.NumberFormat("en-US", { style: "currency", currency: "USD", minimumFractionDigits: 0, maximumFractionDigits: 0 });
const pct2 = new Intl.NumberFormat("en-US", { minimumFractionDigits: 2, maximumFractionDigits: 2 });
---
<BaseLayout title={title} description={description} canonicalPath="/guides/credit-card-payment-payoff-calculator">
  <section class="card hero">
    <span class="pill">Guide</span>
    <nav class="breadcrumbs" aria-label="Breadcrumb">
      <a href="/">Home</a>
      <span aria-hidden="true">/</span>
      <a href="/guides">Guides</a>
      <span aria-hidden="true">/</span>
      <span aria-current="page">Payment payoff calculator</span>
    </nav>
    <h1>Credit card payment payoff calculator</h1>
    <p>
      A "payment payoff" calculator estimates how long it takes to pay off a balance when you make a fixed monthly payment. This is
      useful for answering "what if I pay $200/month instead of the minimum?"
    </p>
    <div class="btn-row">
      <a class="btn btn-primary" href="/calculators/credit-card-payoff-calculator">Payoff calculator</a>
      <a class="btn" href="/calculators/minimum-payment-payoff-calculator">Minimum payments</a>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="card section prose" style="margin-top:18px">
    <h2 style="margin-top:0">What to enter</h2>
    <ul class="muted" style="margin:10px 0 0; padding-left:18px">
      <li>Current balance</li>
      <li>Purchase APR</li>
      <li>Your planned monthly payment</li>
    </ul>
    <p class="muted" style="margin:12px 0 0">
      Estimates assume no new purchases and a fixed APR. If you keep using the card, payoff time can be much longer.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="card section prose" style="margin-top:18px">
    <h2 style="margin-top:0">Example: why payment size matters</h2>
    <p class="muted" style="margin:10px 0 0">
      If you have a $3,000 balance at 22% APR, monthly interest can be roughly balance x (APR / 12), or about $55 early on. A $100 payment
      reduces principal by roughly $45 in the first month, but a $70 payment reduces principal by only about $15. That difference compounds
      over time and can add months (or years) to payoff.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="card section prose" style="margin-top:18px">
    <h2 style="margin-top:0">How to choose a realistic monthly payment</h2>
    <ul class="muted" style="margin:10px 0 0; padding-left:18px">
      <li>Start with what you can sustain every month, then increase it after you've proven consistency.</li>
      <li>If you have irregular cash flow, test a conservative base payment plus occasional lump-sum payments.</li>
      <li>If your APR may change (promo ends), rerun the scenario with the future APR.</li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <section class="card section prose" style="margin-top:18px">
    <h2 style="margin-top:0">Worked example: fixed payment vs higher payment</h2>
    <p class="muted" style="margin:10px 0 0">
      Example: {money0.format(exampleBalance)} at {pct2.format(exampleApr)}% APR. Compare two fixed payments to see how payoff time and total
      interest change.
    </p>
    <div style="overflow:auto; margin-top:12px">
      <table class="table">
        <thead>
          <tr>
            <th class="num">Monthly payment</th>
            <th class="num">Payoff time</th>
            <th class="num">Total interest</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr>
            <td class="num">{money0.format(examplePaymentA)}</td>
            <td class="num">{payoffA.months == null ? "N/A" : `${payoffA.months} months`}</td>
            <td class="num">{money0.format(payoffA.totalInterest)}</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td class="num">{money0.format(examplePaymentB)}</td>
            <td class="num">{payoffB.months == null ? "N/A" : `${payoffB.months} months`}</td>
            <td class="num">{money0.format(payoffB.totalInterest)}</td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>
    <p class="muted" style="margin:12px 0 0">
      In this example, increasing the payment by {money0.format(examplePaymentB - examplePaymentA)} saves about{' '}
      {money0.format(Math.max(0, payoffA.totalInterest - payoffB.totalInterest))} in interest and shortens the timeline. A payment under{' '}
      {money0.format(payoffA.minPaymentToAvoidGrowth)} would not reduce the balance.
    </p>
  </section>
  <section class="grid" style="margin-top:18px">
    <div class="card section prose col-6">
      <h2 style="margin-top:0">How to use results</h2>
      <ul class="muted" style="margin:10px 0 0; padding-left:18px">
        <li>Compare multiple payment amounts ($200 vs $250 vs $300).</li>
        <li>Look at total interest, not just payoff date.</li>
        <li>If your payment is close to monthly interest, payoff can take a long time.</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
    <div class="card section prose col-6">
      <h2 style="margin-top:0">Common pitfalls</h2>
      <ul class="muted" style="margin:10px 0 0; padding-left:18px">
        <li>Forgetting fees and new purchases.</li>
        <li>Assuming APR/12 matches statement interest exactly (many issuers use daily interest).</li>
        <li>Not accounting for APR changes (promo ends, penalty APR).</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="card section prose" style="margin-top:18px">
    <h2 style="margin-top:0">Checklist: set a payment you can keep</h2>
    <ul class="muted" style="margin:10px 0 0; padding-left:18px">
      <li>Confirm the payment is above the monthly interest so the balance actually falls.</li>
      <li>Set autopay for the minimum plus a fixed extra amount you can sustain.</li>
      <li>Rerun the scenario if your APR changes or you plan a balance transfer.</li>
      <li>Stop new purchases on the payoff card to keep the plan on track.</li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <section class="card section prose" style="margin-top:18px">
    <h2 style="margin-top:0">FAQ</h2>
    <h3 style="margin:12px 0 0">Why does payoff look so slow at first?</h3>
    <p class="muted" style="margin:8px 0 0">
      Early payments are mostly interest because the balance is highest. As the balance drops, more of each payment goes to principal and
      the payoff pace accelerates.
    </p>
    <h3 style="margin:12px 0 0">What if I keep making new purchases?</h3>
    <p class="muted" style="margin:8px 0 0">
      The payoff estimate assumes no new charges. New purchases keep the balance higher and can extend the payoff timeline substantially.
    </p>
    <h3 style="margin:12px 0 0">Should I use minimum payment or fixed payment?</h3>
    <p class="muted" style="margin:8px 0 0">
      A fixed payment is usually better for planning because you control the timeline. Minimum payments can stretch payoff for years.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="card section prose" style="margin-top:18px">
    <h2 style="margin-top:0">References</h2>
    <ul class="muted" style="margin:10px 0 0; padding-left:18px">
      <li>
        CFPB:{' '}
        <a href="https://www.consumerfinance.gov/consumer-tools/credit-cards/" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank">
          Credit card resources
        </a>
      </li>
    </ul>
  </section>
  <section class="card section prose" style="margin-top:18px">
    <h2 style="margin-top:0">Next steps</h2>
    <div class="btn-row" style="margin-top:10px">
      <a class="btn btn-primary" href="/calculators/credit-card-payoff-calculator">Model a fixed payment</a>
      <a class="btn" href="/guides/calculate-credit-card-payoff">How to calculate payoff</a>
      <a class="btn" href="/guides/credit-card-payoff-strategy">Payoff strategy</a>
      <a class="btn" href="/topics/credit-cards">Credit cards hub</a>
    </div>
    <p class="muted" style="margin:12px 0 0">Educational use only. Not financial advice.</p>
    <p class="muted" style="margin:12px 0 0; font-size:13px">Last updated: 2026-01-28</p>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>
